metadata.name: Illuminations #211
metadata.description:
Created for the FxHash Turns One week - Thank you FxHash for all the opportunities you have given generative artists and collectors, and thank you to everyone who makes, and collects, the great art here. Here are a few celebratory generative effects which come from my 2022 experiments on random walks through color and space.

There are 5 different burst patterns (Whirligig, Sky Ripple, Confetti, Classic, Sparkler) and the Cocktail type brings them all together (somewhat chaotically)

To continue with the display after it stops press c

To switch to tranquil mode press t - You will want to try this out when you have a minute

To switch back to live mode press v

To stop the display process press x

To save a 2800x2800 jpg press s

Made with p5.js - all proceeds and royalties assigned to the Processing Foundation (who also deserve a big thank you)

This work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License.

metadata.name: lineJag_aliasing #16
metadata.description:
The jaggies created by the lines create smooth noise.
Are they pretending not to notice, or are they really invisible? There is not a single line that is truly loose.
I really want to find evidence that no line is loose.
But I keep finding it and hiding it, then finding it and hiding it.
Still, I feel a little fear and respect for the fact that the straight line connecting "somewhere" and "somewhere" is built on the trust that they are connected, when they are not really connected.

metadata.name: Smile_Bamboo #23
metadata.description:
From within a single acupuncture point, a trunk stretches out, like a bamboo, in a straight line and at different angles.

One leaf. And one round fruit.
It is like a smile, the one we are always looking for.

A smile is what I seek from day to day.
Just a straight, pure smile.

I felt as if I would lose such a natural expression as a human being at any moment.

I began to wish for a code, a number to smile at me again.

I can't draw faces in sketches well.
But I enjoyed reloading over and over again, hoping to find a smile somewhere in the randomness of this code.


May the world be filled with smiles.
That is all I pray for.

Asahamiz

metadata.name: The Way of Thinking #15
metadata.description:
How do thoughts form and evolve? Do they harmonize or stand alone? Do they collide or coalesce? In "The Way of Thinking" I’ve tried to capture the essence of thought — the raw genesis, the dynamic transformation, and the interplay of associations in the mind's labyrinthine corridors.

I was longly inspired by the strict bounds of math and physics. Now it’s a time to set myself free into an unpredictable organic world. This artwork is my first exploration of differential growth algorithms where each particle moves, interacts with others, and multiplies as thoughts in our minds.

Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience. Chrome is highly recommended for high res saving.

Made with love and p5js.


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG at current resolution
[2] - save PNG 5000 x 5000
[3] - save PNG 5000 x 5000 without grain
